Part 1 — What Happens After the API Gateway
We start from this point in the architecture:

User → Internet → API Gateway
The API Gateway is the last component exposed directly to the internet.
Everything after it exists inside the private network.

1. Crossing Trust Boundary 2 (Edge → Application Network)
After the API Gateway processes the request, it forwards traffic into the private application subnet.
The reason this boundary exists is simple:
Public internet traffic must not directly reach internal services
So the gateway becomes the single controlled entry point.

2. Application Services Layer (Private Subnet)
Inside the private subnet we have microservices.
                 Private Application Subnet
        +------------------------------------------+
        | Auth Service                             |
        | Document Ingestion Service               |
        | Metadata Processing Service              |
        | Job Queue                                |
        +------------------------------------------+
These services run in containers on orchestrated infrastructure such as Kubernetes.
Each service performs a different responsibility.

2.1 Flow A — Authentication
First request flow:
User → API Gateway → Auth Service
Example:
POST /login
POST /upload-document
The Auth service:
• validates credentials
• generates access tokens
• enforces identity rules
After authentication succeeds, the request continues to other services.

2.2 Flow B — Document Upload
Next flow:
API Gateway → Document Ingestion Service
Example request:
POST /documents/upload
The ingestion service performs several actions.
Subflow:
Upload request
      │
      ▼
Store file temporarily
      │
      ▼
Generate metadata
      │
      ▼
Send processing job to queue
This service does not run heavy AI models.
Its purpose is simply accepting and registering the document.

3. Internal Service Communication (Service Mesh)
Inside the application layer, services communicate with each other.
But they do not talk directly.
Instead communication passes through a service mesh such as Istio.
Architecture:
Service Container
       │
       ▼
Sidecar Proxy

Actual communication flow becomes:
Service A
   │
   ▼
Proxy A
   │
   │ encrypted mTLS traffic
   ▼
Proxy B
   │
   ▼
Service B

This layer handles:
service authentication
encrypted traffic
service identity verification
Without this layer, any compromised service could impersonate another.

4. Job Queue System
After the ingestion service processes a document, it creates a processing job.
Upload Service → Job Queue
The queue exists because AI processing is slow.
Architecture:
User uploads document
        │
        ▼
Job queue stores processing request
        │
        ▼
AI workers consume jobs asynchronously

Typical queue technologies include:
message brokers
streaming systems
task queues
The queue separates:
user interaction speed
AI processing speed

5. Crossing Trust Boundary 3 (Application → Worker Cluster)
Now the system moves to the AI processing environment.
Why this boundary exists:
AI workers execute complex workloads
They should not be reachable by normal services
So they are placed in another subnet or cluster.

6. AI Processing Subnet
AI workers handle:
document parsing
model inference
data extraction

Architecture:
AI Worker Cluster
+------------------------------------+
| Worker Pod                         |
|                                    |
| Document Parser                    |
| AI Model Runtime                   |
|                                    |
+------------------------------------+
Worker flow:
Worker polls queue
        │
        ▼
Retrieve document
        │
        ▼
Run model inference
        │
        ▼
Store results
Workers may also call internal APIs during processing.

7. Crossing Trust Boundary 4 (Processing → Data Layer)
Data storage is the most sensitive zone.
So it lives in a separate subnet.

8. Data Storage Layer
This layer contains two main components.
Data Subnet
+--------------------------------------+
| Metadata Database                    |
| Object Storage Access Proxy          |
+--------------------------------------+
Metadata database
Stores:
document metadata
processing status
user ownership
results
Object storage proxy
Documents themselves are stored in object storage systems.

The proxy exists because:
direct storage access should not be allowed from all services
So the flow becomes:
AI Worker
   │
   ▼
Storage Proxy
   │
   ▼
Object Storage

9. Control Plane (Infrastructure Management)
This system runs on container orchestration infrastructure.
Control plane architecture:
Control Plane
+--------------------------------+
| Kubernetes API Server          |
| Scheduler                      |
| Controller Manager             |
+--------------------------------+

Responsibilities:
schedule containers
manage cluster state
deploy new services

Control plane traffic:
Control Plane → Worker Nodes
This traffic is management traffic, not user data.

That’s why the architecture separates:
Control plane
Data plane

10. Admin Plane
Now consider human administrators.
Engineers need access to manage systems.
Access flow:
Engineer Laptop
       │
       ▼
Identity Provider
       │
       ▼
Admin Gateway
       │
       ▼
Bastion Host
       │
       ▼
Internal servers
The bastion acts as a jump server.
Engineers connect there before reaching internal infrastructure.


