-> Kill Chain:
Realistic Attacker Kill Chain
Now we walk through how an attacker might try to move through this architecture.

. Stage 1 — Initial Entry
Attack begins at:
Internet → API Gateway
Attacker sends malicious requests:
API exploitation
authentication attacks
input manipulation

Goal:
compromise a backend service

. Stage 2 — Compromise Application Service
Attacker gains control of a container:
Application Service compromised
Example outcome:
remote shell inside container
Now attacker attempts:
internal service discovery

. Stage 3 — Lateral Movement
Attacker scans internal network:
Compromised Service
       │
       ▼
Discover other microservices

Possible actions:
call internal APIs
probe service mesh endpoints
access internal queues

Goal:
reach privileged services

. Stage 4 — Access Job Queue
Attacker interacts with queue system:
Compromised Service → Job Queue

Possible attack:
submit malicious jobs
modify processing tasks

This could cause:
execution of attacker-controlled workloads

Stage 5 — AI Worker Compromise
Malicious job executes on worker:
Queue → AI Worker
Now attacker gains access to:
worker environment
model runtime
filesystem

Workers may have access to:
documents
processing results

Stage 6 — Data Access
From the worker environment:
Worker → Storage Proxy
Worker → Metadata Database

Attacker may attempt:
data extraction
unauthorized queries

Goal:
exfiltrate sensitive documents

Stage 7 — Control Plane Escalation
Attacker tries to move upward.

Compromised Worker
       │
       ▼
Attempt Kubernetes API access

If control plane credentials are accessible:
cluster takeover possible

Stage 8 — Admin Plane Targeting
Separately, attacker may target administrators.

Example attack:
phishing engineer
stealing admin credentials

Then attacker attempts:
Admin Gateway login

If successful:
full infrastructure control

